{"questionId":"27964","questionHtml":"<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Six restaurant locations (labelled <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>A</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>E</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>F</mtext></math>) are shown, together with their Voronoi&nbsp;diagram. All distances are measured in kilometres.</p>\n<p style=\"text-align:center;\"><img src=\"__IMG__/acc0315b5119f8e934ef7f20a3ae6df2c39a32af.png\"></p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Restaurant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math> is at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>)</mo></math> and restaurant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math> is at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Restaurant <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math> is at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>(</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>)</mo></math>.</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-parent-stem\"><p>Hence find</p></div>\n<div class=\"qb-leaf-prompt\"><p>the coordinates of the point which is of equal distance from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>B</mtext></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>C</mtext></math> and <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>D</mtext></math>.</p></div>","markschemeHtml":"<p>attempt to find the intersection of two perpendicular bisectors (<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BC</mtext></math> &amp; <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>CD</mtext></math>)&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>(M1)</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> This may be seen graphically or algebraically.</p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>17</mn></math></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> Accept equivalent methods using the perpendicular bisector of <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>BD</mtext></math>,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mfenced><mrow><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp; OR&nbsp;&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>x</mi><mo>-</mo><mn>14</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math></p>\n<p><br><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mi>y</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></math>&nbsp; <strong>OR&nbsp;&nbsp;</strong><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfenced><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>,</mo><mo>&nbsp;</mo><mn>6</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced></math>&nbsp;&nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp; &nbsp;<em><strong>A1</strong></em></p>\n<p><br><strong>Note:</strong> The <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi></math>-coordinate must be exact or expressed to at least <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>3</mn></math> sf.</p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>\n<p><em><strong>[2 marks]</strong></em></p>","meta":{"questionId":"27964","referenceCode":"22N.2.SL.TZ0.3d.i","subjectId":"51-dp-mathematics-applications-and-interpretation","title":"the coordinates of the point which is of equal distance from B, C and D.","paper":"2","level":"SL","questionNumber":"d.i","marksAvailable":"[Maximum mark: 2]","breadcrumbLabels":["Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","Topic 3—Geometry and trigonometry","SL 3.6—Voronoi diagrams"],"memberSectionIds":[],"sectionOrders":{}},"schemaVersion":2}